    print(number1 + number2)































3. What will this code print out?

number1 = 5
number2 = 89

def checkSumOfNumbers(num1, num2):
    num3 = num1 + num2 - 4

    if num3 > 90:
        return "oui"
    elif num3 < 90:
        return "non"

    if num3 < num2:
        return "bien"
    else:
        return "mal"


responce = checkSumOfNumbers(number1, number2)

print(responce)


A: oui

B: non

C: bien

D: mal





























I will be very very impressed if anyone gets this question

One note: adding strings together is possible using " ".join(), so:

words = ["hi", "hello"] 
joined = " ".join(words)  ----  this will be "hi hello"

Another note: to convert numbers to strings you can use str() so: str(7.8) = "7.8"

4. How would the print() function be defined? Pretend that console.write() can write to the console

A: 

def print(a, b, c, d, e):
    words = [a, b, c, d, e]
    console.write(" ".join(words)).str()


B: 

def print(*words):
    console.write(str(*word) in words).join()


C:

def print(*words):
    console.write(" ".join(str(word) for word in words))


D:

def print(a, b, c, d, e):
    words = [str(a), str(b), str(c), str(d), str(e)]
    console.write(" ".join(words))